<!-- SECTION 1 -->
<div>
    <h2>1. Project Overview</h2>
    <p>
        The Rental Management System is a web service designed to facilitate tenancy leases, property listings, and secure user management. Built with FastAPI and backed by a relational PostgreSQL database, it provides robust APIs that allow landlords to list rental properties and tenants to search for and lease available accommodations.
    </p>
    <p>
        Security is managed using industry-standard JSON Web Tokens (JWT) for authentication. Additionally, role-based authorization enforces access control, ensuring only authorized landlord accounts can modify property listings while tenant accounts are permitted to sign tenancy contracts.
    </p>
</div>

<div class="page-break"></div>

<!-- SECTION 2 -->
<div>
    <h2>2. Technology Stack & Tools Used</h2>
    <p>The following tools and frameworks were utilized to build and run the application:</p>
    
    <table>
        <tr>
            <th>Technology / Tool</th>
            <th>Purpose & Role in Project</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>FastAPI</b></td>
            <td>Python web framework used for designing the RESTful endpoints, validating requests, and generating automatic Swagger documentation.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>PostgreSQL</b></td>
            <td>Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) used for secure, relational, and persistent data storage.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>SQLAlchemy</b></td>
            <td>Object-Relational Mapping (ORM) library used to interact with the PostgreSQL database using Python classes (models) instead of raw SQL queries.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>Uvicorn</b></td>
            <td>Asynchronous Server Gateway Interface (ASGI) web server used to run the FastAPI application locally.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>Pydantic</b></td>
            <td>Data parsing and validation library used to define request and response payloads (schemas) with strict type checking.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>python-jose & bcrypt</b></td>
            <td>Libraries used to securely hash user passwords (using bcrypt) and generate/validate signed JSON Web Tokens (JWT).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>Postman</b></td>
            <td>API client used for manually calling, testing, and verifying the routes during development.</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</div>

<div class="page-break"></div>

<!-- SECTION 3 -->
<div>
    <h2>3. Database Schema Design (ER)</h2>
    <p>
        The relational database schema is structured into three main tables: <b>users</b>, <b>properties</b>, and <b>leases</b>. Below is the relational structure of the tables:
    </p>
    
    <h3>3.1 Database Tables</h3>
    
    <b>Users Table (users)</b>
    <table>
        <tr>
            <th>Column Name</th>
            <th>Data Type</th>
            <th>Constraints</th>
            <th>Description</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>id</td>
            <td>VARCHAR</td>
            <td>Primary Key</td>
            <td>Unique identifier (UUID) generated on signup.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>username</td>
            <td>VARCHAR</td>
            <td>Non-nullable</td>
            <td>The display name of the user.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>email</td>
            <td>VARCHAR</td>
            <td>Unique, Non-nullable</td>
            <td>User's email address (used for login).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>password</td>
            <td>VARCHAR</td>
            <td>Non-nullable</td>
            <td>Salted and hashed password.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>role</td>
            <td>VARCHAR</td>
            <td>Default: 'tenant'</td>
            <td>Access role: 'landlord' or 'tenant'.</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <b>Properties Table (properties)</b>
    <table>
        <tr>
            <th>Column Name</th>
            <th>Data Type</th>
            <th>Constraints</th>
            <th>Description</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>id</td>
            <td>INTEGER</td>
            <td>Primary Key, Autoincrement</td>
            <td>Unique identifier for the property listing.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>title</td>
            <td>VARCHAR</td>
            <td>Non-nullable</td>
            <td>Heading/title of the property.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>description</td>
            <td>TEXT</td>
            <td>Nullable</td>
            <td>Detailed description.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>address</td>
            <td>VARCHAR</td>
            <td>Non-nullable</td>
            <td>Physical location of the property.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>price_per_month</td>
            <td>DOUBLE PRECISION</td>
            <td>Non-nullable</td>
            <td>Monthly rental cost.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>is_available</td>
            <td>BOOLEAN</td>
            <td>Default: True</td>
            <td>Tracks if the property is currently rentable.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>owner_id</td>
            <td>VARCHAR</td>
            <td>Foreign Key</td>
            <td>References <i>users(id)</i> (Landlord only).</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <b>Leases Table (leases)</b>
    <table>
        <tr>
            <th>Column Name</th>
            <th>Data Type</th>
            <th>Constraints</th>
            <th>Description</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>id</td>
            <td>INTEGER</td>
            <td>Primary Key, Autoincrement</td>
            <td>Unique identifier for the lease contract.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>property_id</td>
            <td>INTEGER</td>
            <td>Foreign Key</td>
            <td>References <i>properties(id)</i>.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>tenant_id</td>
            <td>VARCHAR</td>
            <td>Foreign Key</td>
            <td>References <i>users(id)</i>.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>start_date</td>
            <td>DATE</td>
            <td>Non-nullable</td>
            <td>Lease start date.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>end_date</td>
            <td>DATE</td>
            <td>Non-nullable</td>
            <td>Lease expiration date.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>rent_amount</td>
            <td>DOUBLE PRECISION</td>
            <td>Non-nullable</td>
            <td>Agreed monthly rent.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>status</td>
            <td>VARCHAR</td>
            <td>Default: 'active'</td>
            <td>Lease status ('active' or 'terminated').</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</div>

<div class="page-break"></div>

<!-- SECTION 4 -->
<div>
    <h2>4. Application Architecture</h2>
    <p>
        The application is built on a layered architecture separating routing, validation, business logic, and database persistence:
    </p>
    
    <div class="code-block">
  [ Client Request ]
         │ (HTTP Request with Headers & JSON payload)
         ▼
  [ API Routers (app.py) ]
         │ (Routes requests to endpoint functions)
         ▼
  [ Auth / Role Check Dependencies (dependencies.py) ]
         │ (Validates JWT tokens & checks roles)
         ▼
  [ Schemas validation (schemas.py) ]
         │ (Ensures request and response schemas are valid)
         ▼
  [ SQLAlchemy Session Manager (database.py) ]
         │ (Translates operations into SQL transactions)
         ▼
  [ PostgreSQL Database (rental_db) ]
    </div>
    
    <h3>4.1 Request Flow and Business Rules</h3>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
        <li><b>Authentication Check</b>: Endpoint paths that require authentication use the <i>get_current_user</i> dependency, which decodes the JWT token from the HTTP Bearer header, validates it against the signing key, and retrieves the matching user record from the database.</li>
        <li><b>Role Restriction</b>: Landlord endpoints (e.g. creating/updating properties) are protected by <i>check_landlord</i>, which returns a 403 Forbidden error if a tenant tries to list a house.</li>
        <li><b>Lease Automation</b>: When a tenant successfully leases a property (`POST /leases`), the system automatically registers the lease in the database and updates the property's `is_available` column to `False`. When a lease is terminated (`POST /leases/{id}/terminate`), the property availability is set back to `True`.</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<div class="page-break"></div>

<!-- SECTION 5 -->
<div>
    <h2>5. Postman Integration & Testing Guide</h2>
    <p>
        Postman was used extensively to verify and interact with the backend endpoints during testing. Below are the steps to execute requests in Postman:
    </p>

    <h3>5.1 Sign Up (`POST /signup`)</h3>
    <p>
        Sends user registration payload as a JSON object:
    </p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
        <li><b>URL</b>: <code>http://127.0.0.1:8000/signup</code></li>
        <li><b>Method</b>: POST</li>
        <li><b>Headers</b>: <code>Content-Type: application/json</code></li>
        <li><b>Body</b> (raw JSON):
            <div class="code-block">{
    "username": "Vinay Sharma",
    "email": "vinays@google.com",
    "password": "vinay12345",
    "role": "landlord"
}</div>
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h3>5.2 Login & Token Retrieval (`POST /login`)</h3>
    <p>
        FastAPI uses the OAuth2 standard, which expects credentials as URL-encoded Form Data rather than raw JSON.
    </p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
        <li><b>URL</b>: <code>http://127.0.0.1:8000/login</code></li>
        <li><b>Method</b>: POST</li>
        <li><b>Body</b>: Select <b>x-www-form-urlencoded</b> and enter key-values:
            <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li><code>username</code>: vinays@google.com (or username)</li>
                <li><code>password</code>: vinay12345</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><b>Result</b>: Retreives a response containing <code>access_token</code>, <code>refresh_token</code>, and <code>token_type</code>. Copy the <code>access_token</code> string.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>5.3 Calling Authenticated Routes (e.g., `POST /properties`)</h3>
    <p>
        To access protected endpoints, you must include the token in your headers:
    </p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
        <li><b>URL</b>: <code>http://127.0.0.1:8000/properties</code></li>
        <li><b>Method</b>: POST</li>
        <li><b>Authorization Tab</b>:
            <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li><b>Type</b>: Select <i>Bearer Token</i>.</li>
                <li><b>Token</b>: Paste the copied <code>access_token</code> string.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><b>Body</b> (raw JSON):
            <div class="code-block">{
    "title": "Beautiful Villa",
    "description": "3 BHK Spacious Villa with garden.",
    "address": "45 Green Avenues, Pune",
    "price_per_month": 45000.0
}</div>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>

</body>
